.TH eroosterctl-user-delete 1 "June 2026" "eroosterctl" "Erooster Manual"
.SH NAME
eroosterctl\-user\-delete \- delete a mail user (aliases: \fBdel\fR, \fBrm\fR)
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B eroosterctl user delete
\fIemail\fR
[\fI\-\-yes\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
Removes the specified user from the database. This operation cannot be undone.
Any stored mail for that user remains on disk in the maildir; it is not
removed automatically.
.P
Unless \fB\-\-yes\fR is passed (or \fBeroosterctl \-y\fR) and stdin is a TTY,
the user is prompted to confirm deletion. In non\-interactive mode (non\-TTY
stdin), \fB\-\-yes\fR is required.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\fIemail\fR
Email address of the user to delete (required positional argument).
.TP
\fB\-y, \-\-yes\fR
Skip the confirmation prompt.
.SH EXAMPLES
.EX
# Interactive deletion with confirmation
eroosterctl user delete alice@example.com

# Scripted deletion (no prompt)
eroosterctl user delete alice@example.com --yes

# Ansible task (global --yes on root command)
eroosterctl -y user delete alice@example.com
.EE
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
\fB0\fR
User deleted.
.TP
\fB1\fR
User not found or database error.
.TP
\fB2\fR
\fB\-\-yes\fR required but not provided in non\-interactive mode.
.SH SEE ALSO
\fBeroosterctl\-user\fR(1),
\fBeroosterctl\-user\-add\fR(1),
\fBeroosterctl\-user\-list\fR(1)
